const e=[{text:"I have one message: Christ is the answer.",textEs:"Tengo un mensaje: Cristo es la respuesta.",textPt:"Tenho uma mensagem: Cristo é a resposta.",author:"Billy Graham"},{text:"Make Christ the main object of your life.",textEs:"Haz de Cristo el objetivo principal de tu vida.",textPt:"Faça de Cristo o objetivo principal de sua vida.",author:"Billy Graham"},{text:"God has given us two hands, one to receive with and the other to give with.",textEs:"Dios nos ha dado dos manos, una para recibir y otra para dar.",textPt:"Deus nos deu duas mãos, uma para receber e outra para dar.",author:"Billy Graham"},{text:"The greatest peace is simply to know that the eternal God is our Father through Jesus Christ.",textEs:"La mayor paz es simplemente saber que el Dios eterno es nuestro Padre a través de Jesucristo.",textPt:"A maior paz é simplesmente saber que o Deus eterno é nosso Pai através de Jesus Cristo.",author:"Billy Graham"},{text:"Hardship often prepares an ordinary person for an extraordinary destiny.",textEs:"La adversidad a menudo prepara a una persona ordinaria para un destino extraordinario.",textPt:"A dificuldade muitas vezes prepara uma pessoa comum para um destino extraordinário.",author:"C.S. Lewis"},{text:"The son of God became man to enable men to become sons of God.",textEs:"El Hijo de Dios se hizo hombre para permitir que los hombres se conviertan en hijos de Dios.",textPt:"O Filho de Deus se tornou homem para que os homens se tornassem filhos de Deus.",author:"C.S. Lewis"},{text:"If we find ourselves with a desire that nothing in this world can satisfy, the most probable explanation is that we were made for another world.",textEs:"Si nos encontramos con un deseo que nada en este mundo puede satisfacer, la explicación más probable es que fuimos hechos para otro mundo.",textPt:"Se nos encontramos com um desejo que nada neste mundo pode satisfazer, a explicação mais provável é que fomos feitos para outro mundo.",author:"C.S. Lewis"},{text:"Miracles, in the sense of phenomena we cannot explain, surround us on every hand.",textEs:"Los milagros, en el sentido de fenómenos que no podemos explicar, nos rodean por todas partes.",textPt:"Milagres, no sentido de fenômenos que não podemos explicar, nos cercam por todos os lados.",author:"C.S. Lewis"},{text:"Aim at heaven and you will get earth thrown in. Aim at earth and you will get neither.",textEs:"Apunta al cielo y obtendrás la tierra de regalo. Apunta a la tierra y no obtendrás nada.",textPt:"Almeje o céu e você obterá a terra como bônus. Almeje a terra e não obterá nada.",author:"C.S. Lewis"},{text:"The function of prayer is not to influence God, but rather to change the nature of the one who prays.",textEs:"La función de la oración no es influir en Dios, sino cambiar la naturaleza de quien ora.",textPt:"A função da oração não é influenciar Deus, mas mudar a natureza de quem ora.",author:"Søren Kierkegaard"},{text:"Corrie, your whole life has been a training for the work you are doing here.",textEs:"Corrie, toda tu vida ha sido un entrenamiento para la obra que estás haciendo aquí.",textPt:"Corrie, toda a sua vida foi um treinamento para a obra que você está fazendo aqui.",author:"Corrie ten Boom"},{text:"Hold everything loosely. Only Christ should be held tightly.",textEs:"Sostén todo con soltura. Solo Cristo debe ser sostenido firmemente.",textPt:"Segure tudo levemente. Apenas Cristo deve ser seguro firmemente.",author:"Corrie ten Boom"},{text:"The mark of a Christian is not perfection, but progression.",textEs:"La marca de un cristiano no es la perfección, sino la progresión.",textPt:"A marca de um cristão não é a perfeição, mas a progressão.",author:"Corrie ten Boom"},{text:"There is no pit so deep that God's love is not deeper still.",textEs:"No hay pozo tan profundo que el amor de Dios no sea más profundo aún.",textPt:"Não há abismo tão profundo que o amor de Deus não seja ainda mais profundo.",author:"Corrie ten Boom"},{text:"I felt as if I had been born anew.",textEs:"Sentí como si hubiera nacido de nuevo.",textPt:"Senti como se tivesse nascido de novo.",author:"Mother Teresa"},{text:"In the poor, I see the face of Jesus.",textEs:"En los pobres, veo el rostro de Jesús.",textPt:"Nos pobres, vejo o rosto de Jesus.",author:"Mother Teresa"},{text:"Love in action is service.",textEs:"El amor en acción es servicio.",textPt:"O amor em ação é serviço.",author:"Mother Teresa"},{text:"When the Holy Spirit fills you, He gives you power to be a witness.",textEs:"Cuando el Espíritu Santo te llena, te da poder para ser un testigo.",textPt:"Quando o Espírito Santo te enche, Ele te dá poder para ser uma testemunha.",author:"David Yonggi Cho"},{text:"Not all of us can do great things. But we can do small things with great love.",textEs:"No todos podemos hacer cosas grandes. Pero podemos hacer cosas pequeñas con gran amor.",textPt:"Nem todos podemos fazer grandes coisas. Mas podemos fazer pequenas coisas com grande amor.",author:"Mother Teresa"},{text:"God loves us unconditionally and forever.",textEs:"Dios nos ama sin condiciones y por siempre.",textPt:"Deus nos ama incondicionalmente e para sempre.",author:"Dietrich Bonhoeffer"},{text:"Silence in the face of evil is itself evil.",textEs:"El silencio ante el mal es en sí mismo un mal.",textPt:"O silêncio perante o mal é em si um mal.",author:"Dietrich Bonhoeffer"},{text:"Not to act is to act; not to decide is to decide.",textEs:"No actuar es actuar; no decidir es decidir.",textPt:"Não agir é agir; não decidir é decidir.",author:"Dietrich Bonhoeffer"},{text:"Who am I? They mock me, these lonely questions of mine.",textEs:"¿Quién soy yo? Se burlan de mí, estas preguntas solitarias de las mías.",textPt:"Quem sou eu? Zombam de mim, estas solitárias perguntas minhas.",author:"Dietrich Bonhoeffer"},{text:"I believe that what we suffer in this world can never be compensation for the glory that will be revealed in us.",textEs:"Creo que lo que sufrimos en este mundo nunca puede ser compensación por la gloria que se revelará en nosotros.",textPt:"Acredito que o que sofremos neste mundo nunca pode ser compensação pela glória que será revelada em nós.",author:"Dietrich Bonhoeffer"},{text:"What comes into our minds when we think about God is the most important thing about us.",textEs:"Lo que viene a nuestra mente cuando pensamos en Dios es lo más importante de nosotros.",textPt:"O que vem à nossa mente quando pensamos em Deus é a coisa mais importante sobre nós.",author:"A.W. Tozer"},{text:"Endless forms of religious deception are available to those who want to avoid facing God.",textEs:"Hay formas infinitas de engaño religioso disponibles para quienes quieren evitar enfrentar a Dios.",textPt:"Formas infinitas de engano religioso estão disponíveis para aqueles que querem evitar enfrentar a Deus.",author:"A.W. Tozer"},{text:"We learn by doing. But we become wise by understanding.",textEs:"Aprendemos haciendo. Pero nos hacemos sabios por comprender.",textPt:"Aprendemos fazendo. Mas nos tornamos sábios por compreender.",author:"A.W. Tozer"},{text:"Faith is taking the first step even when you don't see the whole staircase.",textEs:"La fe es dar el primer paso aun cuando no ves toda la escalera.",textPt:"A fé é dar o primeiro passo mesmo quando você não consegue ver toda a escadaria.",author:"Martin Luther King Jr."},{text:"Darkness cannot drive out darkness. Only light can do that. Hate cannot drive out hate. Only love can do that.",textEs:"La oscuridad no puede expulsar la oscuridad. Solo la luz puede hacerlo. El odio no puede expulsar el odio. Solo el amor puede hacerlo.",textPt:"A escuridão não pode expulsar a escuridão. Apenas a luz pode fazer isso. O ódio não pode expulsar o ódio. Apenas o amor pode fazer isso.",author:"Martin Luther King Jr."},{text:"No man can choose his own creed. Faith is not our own work; it is the work of God in us.",textEs:"Ningún hombre puede elegir su propio credo. La fe no es nuestra obra; es la obra de Dios en nosotros.",textPt:"Ninguém pode escolher sua própria crença. A fé não é nossa obra; é a obra de Deus em nós.",author:"Oswald Chambers"},{text:"Have you noticed that life never intends for you to succeed until you are willing to die?",textEs:"¿Has notado que la vida nunca intenta que tengas éxito hasta que estés dispuesto a morir?",textPt:"Você notou que a vida nunca pretende que você tenha sucesso até estar disposto a morrer?",author:"Oswald Chambers"},{text:"Never support an experience which does not have God as its source and faith in God as its result.",textEs:"Nunca apoyes una experiencia que no tenga a Dios como su fuente y fe en Dios como su resultado.",textPt:"Nunca apoie uma experiência que não tenha Deus como sua fonte e fé em Deus como seu resultado.",author:"Oswald Chambers"},{text:"In discouragement, we lose sight of His trustworthiness and focus on our own unworthiness.",textEs:"En el desánimo, perdemos de vista su confiabilidad y nos enfocamos en nuestra propia indignidad.",textPt:"No desânimo, perdemos de vista sua confiabilidade e focamos em nossa própria indignidade.",author:"Elisabeth Elliot"},{text:"Frustration is the result of unfulfilled expectations. Don't expect anything from the world.",textEs:"La frustración es el resultado de expectativas no cumplidas. No esperes nada del mundo.",textPt:"A frustração é o resultado de expectativas não realizadas. Não espere nada do mundo.",author:"Elisabeth Elliot"},{text:"The will of God is the only thing that can make anyone truly happy.",textEs:"La voluntad de Dios es la única cosa que puede hacer a alguien verdaderamente feliz.",textPt:"A vontade de Deus é a única coisa que pode fazer alguém verdadeiramente feliz.",author:"Elisabeth Elliot"},{text:"There is a miracle in your mouth. Speak life over your situation.",textEs:"Hay un milagro en tu boca. Habla vida sobre tu situación.",textPt:"Há um milagre na sua boca. Fale vida sobre sua situação.",author:"Reinhard Bonnke"},{text:"God is not looking for golden vessels or silver vessels. He is looking for yielded vessels.",textEs:"Dios no busca vasijas de oro o de plata. Busca vasijas rendidas.",textPt:"Deus não procura vasos de ouro ou de prata. Ele procura vasos rendidos.",author:"Kathryn Kuhlman"},{text:"The Holy Spirit is not an influence. He is a Person. He is God.",textEs:"El Espíritu Santo no es una influencia. Es una Persona. Es Dios.",textPt:"O Espírito Santo não é uma influência. Ele é uma Pessoa. Ele é Deus.",author:"Jack Hayford"},{text:"Signs and wonders follow believers, but seekers of signs and wonders make troublemakers.",textEs:"Las señales y maravillas siguen a los creyentes, pero los que buscan señales y maravillas causan problemas.",textPt:"Sinais e maravilhas seguem os crentes, mas os que procuram sinais e maravilhas causam problemas.",author:"Smith Wigglesworth"},{text:"God is more willing to give to us than we are to ask.",textEs:"Dios está más dispuesto a darnos que nosotros a pedir.",textPt:"Deus está mais disposto a dar a nós do que nós estamos dispostos a pedir.",author:"Smith Wigglesworth"},{text:"Prayer should not be an attempt to bend God's will to ours, but an alignment of our will with His.",textEs:"La oración no debe ser un intento de doblar la voluntad de Dios a la nuestra, sino una alineación de nuestra voluntad con la suya.",textPt:"A oração não deve ser uma tentativa de dobrar a vontade de Deus à nossa, mas um alinhamento de nossa vontade com a Dele.",author:"E.M. Bounds"},{text:"Prayer is the slender nerve that moves the muscle of omnipotence.",textEs:"La oración es el nervio delgado que mueve el músculo de la omnipotencia.",textPt:"A oração é o delgado nervo que move o músculo da onipotência.",author:"E.M. Bounds"},{text:"Let the scribe beware of idle words.",textEs:"Que el escriba se cuide de las palabras ociosas.",textPt:"Que o escriba se cuide das palavras ociosas.",author:"Watchman Nee"},{text:"The cross we bear precedes the crown we wear.",textEs:"La cruz que llevamos precede a la corona que vestimos.",textPt:"A cruz que carregamos precede a coroa que usamos.",author:"Watchman Nee"},{text:"He is no fool who gives what he cannot keep to gain what he cannot lose.",textEs:"No es necio el que da lo que no puede retener para ganar lo que no puede perder.",textPt:"Não é tolo aquele que entrega o que não pode conservar para conquistar o que não pode perder.",author:"Jim Elliot"},{text:"Do not pray for tasks equal to your powers. Pray for powers equal to your tasks.",textEs:"No ores por tareas iguales a tus poderes. Ora por poderes iguales a tus tareas.",textPt:"Não ore por tarefas iguais aos seus poderes. Ore por poderes iguais às suas tarefas.",author:"Jim Elliot"},{text:"God is faithful even when we are faithless.",textEs:"Dios es fiel incluso cuando nosotros somos infieles.",textPt:"Deus é fiel mesmo quando somos infiéis.",author:"Brother Andrew"},{text:"The first rule of the underground is: trust no one completely.",textEs:"La primera regla de la clandestinidad es: no confíes completamente en nadie.",textPt:"A primeira regra da clandestinidade é: não confie completamente em ninguém.",author:"Brother Andrew"},{text:"Every Christian's life is an epistle known and read of all men.",textEs:"La vida de cada cristiano es una epístola conocida y leída por todos los hombres.",textPt:"A vida de cada cristão é uma epístola conhecida e lida por todos os homens.",author:"Lottie Moon"},{text:"I have long held the conviction that the work of a missionary never ends.",textEs:"He mantenido durante mucho tiempo la convicción de que la obra de un misionero nunca termina.",textPt:"Há muito tempo mantenho a convicção de que a obra de um missionário nunca termina.",author:"Lottie Moon"},{text:"We are not merely saving an individual here and there. We are saving the nation, lifting it up from ultimate degradation.",textEs:"No estamos salvando meramente a un individuo aquí y otro allá. Estamos salvando la nación, elevándola desde la degradación final.",textPt:"Não estamos meramente salvando um indivíduo aqui e ali. Estamos salvando a nação, elevando-a da degradação final.",author:"Richard Halverson"},{text:"Man is not at home in the world. He is a wanderer in search of his homeland.",textEs:"El hombre no está en casa en el mundo. Es un vagabundo en busca de su tierra natal.",textPt:"O homem não está em casa no mundo. Ele é um peregrino em busca de sua pátria.",author:"Richard Halverson"},{text:"Revival means returning to God. Revival means to live again.",textEs:"Avivamiento significa volver a Dios. Avivamiento significa vivir de nuevo.",textPt:"Avivamento significa voltar a Deus. Avivamento significa viver de novo.",author:"Adrian Rogers"},{text:"The will of God is the safest place in the universe.",textEs:"La voluntad de Dios es el lugar más seguro del universo.",textPt:"A vontade de Deus é o lugar mais seguro do universo.",author:"Adrian Rogers"},{text:"I never cease to be amazed at the creative power of faith.",textEs:"Nunca dejo de sorprenderme del poder creativo de la fe.",textPt:"Nunca deixo de me maravilhar com o poder criativo da fé.",author:"Vance Havner"},{text:"Feeling is not faith, and faith is not feeling.",textEs:"El sentimiento no es fe, y la fe no es sentimiento.",textPt:"O sentimento não é fé, e a fé não é sentimento.",author:"Vance Havner"},{text:"Revival is the return of the Church from her backslidings, and her advance under the impulse of the Holy Ghost.",textEs:"El avivamiento es el regreso de la Iglesia de sus caídas, y su avance bajo el impulso del Espíritu Santo.",textPt:"Avivamento é o retorno da Igreja de seus desvios, e seu avanço sob o impulso do Espírito Santo.",author:"Leonard Ravenhill"},{text:"God is always bigger than our theology.",textEs:"Dios es siempre más grande que nuestra teología.",textPt:"Deus é sempre maior que nossa teologia.",author:"Leonard Ravenhill"},{text:"I have come to realize that holiness is not the same as being human.",textEs:"He llegado a comprender que la santidad no es lo mismo que ser humano.",textPt:"Cheguei a compreender que a santidade não é o mesmo que ser humano.",author:"E. Stanley Jones"},{text:"Christianity is the most amazing thing in the world because it is the most amazing revelation of God.",textEs:"El cristianismo es lo más asombroso del mundo porque es la revelación más asombrosa de Dios.",textPt:"O cristianismo é a coisa mais incrível do mundo porque é a revelação mais incrível de Deus.",author:"E. Stanley Jones"},{text:"I am going to do all that I can do as long as I live to preach the Gospel of Christ.",textEs:"Voy a hacer todo lo que pueda mientras viva para predicar el Evangelio de Cristo.",textPt:"Vou fazer tudo o que puder enquanto eu viver para pregar o Evangelho de Cristo.",author:"Aimee Semple McPherson"},{text:"I have had the privilege of being enabled to serve the Lord in accordance with the power He gave me.",textEs:"He tenido el privilegio de poder servir al Señor de acuerdo con el poder que me dio.",textPt:"Tive o privilégio de ser capaz de servir ao Senhor de acordo com o poder que Ele me deu.",author:"Aimee Semple McPherson"},{text:"The will of God will not take you where the grace of God cannot sustain you.",textEs:"La voluntad de Dios no te llevará donde la gracia de Dios no pueda sustentarte.",textPt:"A vontade de Deus não o levará aonde a graça de Deus não pode sustentá-lo.",author:"Peter Marshall"},{text:"The measure of a life is not its duration but its donation.",textEs:"La medida de una vida no es su duración sino su donación.",textPt:"A medida de uma vida não está em sua duração, mas em sua doação.",author:"Peter Marshall"},{text:"I am confident that this book is for our day.",textEs:"Estoy convencido de que este libro es para nuestro tiempo.",textPt:"Estou confiante de que este livro é para nosso tempo.",author:"Catherine Marshall"},{text:"Prayer is the greatest force in the universe.",textEs:"La oración es la mayor fuerza del universo.",textPt:"A oração é a maior força do universo.",author:"Catherine Marshall"},{text:"Not because of the law, but because of love, let us work for the salvation of men.",textEs:"No porque de la ley, sino porque del amor, trabajemos por la salvación de los hombres.",textPt:"Não por causa da lei, mas por causa do amor, trabalhemos pela salvação dos homens.",author:"D.L. Moody"},{text:"Prayer is the breath of the soul.",textEs:"La oración es el aliento del alma.",textPt:"A oração é o respiro da alma.",author:"D.L. Moody"},{text:"God's love never gives up on us.",textEs:"El amor de Dios nunca se da por vencido con nosotros.",textPt:"O amor de Deus nunca desiste de nós.",author:"Amy Carmichael"},{text:"You can give without loving, but you cannot love without giving.",textEs:"Puedes dar sin amar, pero no puedes amar sin dar.",textPt:"Você pode dar sem amar, mas não pode amar sem dar.",author:"Amy Carmichael"},{text:"The Bible is not a book of rules. It is a book of promises.",textEs:"La Biblia no es un libro de reglas. Es un libro de promesas.",textPt:"A Bíblia não é um livro de regras. É um livro de promessas.",author:"G. Campbell Morgan"},{text:"Whatever we think about shapes our lives.",textEs:"Lo que pensamos determina nuestras vidas.",textPt:"O que pensamos molda nossas vidas.",author:"G. Campbell Morgan"},{text:"God is willing to work with you right where you are.",textEs:"Dios está dispuesto a trabajar contigo justo donde estás.",textPt:"Deus está disposto a trabalhar com você exatamente onde você está.",author:"Andrew Murray"},{text:"The prayer life is the barometer of the spiritual life.",textEs:"La vida de oración es el barómetro de la vida espiritual.",textPt:"A vida de oração é o barômetro da vida espiritual.",author:"Andrew Murray"},{text:"The prayer of a righteous person has great power as it is working.",textEs:"La oración de una persona justa tiene un gran poder mientras está obrando.",textPt:"A oração de uma pessoa justa tem grande poder enquanto está agindo.",author:"R.A. Torrey"},{text:"Prayer is the key that opens all the treasures of God.",textEs:"La oración es la clave que abre todos los tesoros de Dios.",textPt:"A oração é a chave que abre todos os tesouros de Deus.",author:"R.A. Torrey"},{text:"Teach me, Lord, to understand your statutes; then I will keep them with all my heart.",textEs:"Enséñame, Señor, a entender tus estatutos; entonces los guardaré con todo mi corazón.",textPt:"Ensine-me, Senhor, a entender seus mandamentos; então os guardarei de todo o coração.",author:"Henrietta Mears"},{text:"We are either moving forward or falling back; there is no neutral ground.",textEs:"O estamos avanzando o estamos retrocediendo; no hay terreno neutral.",textPt:"Ou estamos avançando ou recuando; não há meio termo.",author:"Henrietta Mears"},{text:"Man's chief end is to glorify God and enjoy him forever.",textEs:"El fin principal del hombre es glorificar a Dios y disfrutarlo para siempre.",textPt:"O principal objetivo do homem é glorificar a Deus e desfrutá-lo para sempre.",author:"Francis Schaeffer"},{text:"All of life is meant to be lived to the glory of God.",textEs:"Toda la vida debe ser vivida para la gloria de Dios.",textPt:"Toda a vida deve ser vivida para a glória de Deus.",author:"Francis Schaeffer"},{text:"The Bible teaches truth and therefore God is on our side in studying it.",textEs:"La Biblia enseña la verdad y por lo tanto Dios está de nuestro lado al estudiarla.",textPt:"A Bíblia ensina a verdade e, portanto, Deus está ao nosso lado ao estudá-la.",author:"J. Vernon McGee"},{text:"The resurrection of Christ is the cornerstone of Christian faith.",textEs:"La resurrección de Cristo es la piedra angular de la fe cristiana.",textPt:"A ressurreição de Cristo é a pedra angular da fé cristã.",author:"J. Vernon McGee"},{text:"God never made a promise that was too good to be true.",textEs:"Dios nunca hizo una promesa que fuera demasiado buena para ser verdad.",textPt:"Deus nunca fez uma promessa que fosse boa demais para ser verdadeira.",author:"Max Lucado"},{text:"Let God transform you into a new person by changing the way you think.",textEs:"Deja que Dios te transforme en una nueva persona cambiando tu manera de pensar.",textPt:"Deixe Deus te transformar em uma nova pessoa, mudando sua forma de pensar.",author:"Max Lucado"},{text:"His mercy is new every morning.",textEs:"Su misericordia es nueva cada mañana.",textPt:"Sua misericórdia é nova a cada manhã.",author:"Max Lucado"},{text:"God is most glorified in us when we are most satisfied in Him.",textEs:"Dios es más glorificado en nosotros cuando estamos más satisfechos en Él.",textPt:"Deus é mais glorificado em nós quando encontramos nossa maior satisfação nEle.",author:"John Piper"},{text:"Desiring God is a longing that reveals our ultimate purpose.",textEs:"Desear a Dios es un anhelo que revela nuestro propósito definitivo.",textPt:"Desejar a Deus é um anseio que revela nosso propósito final.",author:"John Piper"},{text:"You don't have to be great to start, but you have to start to be great.",textEs:"No tienes que ser grande para empezar, pero tienes que empezar para ser grande.",textPt:"Você não precisa ser grandioso para começar, mas precisa começar para se tornar grandioso.",author:"Rick Warren"},{text:"Purpose is what gives life meaning.",textEs:"El propósito es lo que da significado a la vida.",textPt:"O propósito é o que dá significado à vida.",author:"Rick Warren"},{text:"God will meet you where you are in order to take you where He wants you to go.",textEs:"Dios te encontrará donde estés para llevarte a donde Él quiere que vayas.",textPt:"Deus encontrará você onde você está para te levar aonde Ele quer que você vá.",author:"Tony Evans"},{text:"The throne of God is established on righteousness and justice.",textEs:"El trono de Dios se establece sobre la justicia y la rectitud.",textPt:"O trono de Deus é estabelecido sobre a justiça e a retidão.",author:"Tony Evans"},{text:"Nothing is worth losing Jesus for.",textEs:"Nada merece la pena perder por Jesús.",textPt:"Nada vale a pena perder por Jesus.",author:"Francis Chan"},{text:"We are not cisterns made for hoarding; we are channels made for sharing.",textEs:"No somos cisternas hechas para acumular; somos canales hechos para compartir.",textPt:"Não somos cisternas feitas para acumular; somos canais feitos para compartilhar.",author:"Francis Chan"},{text:"Life is not about how many breaths you take, but how many moments take your breath away.",textEs:"La vida no se trata de cuántas respiraciones respiras, sino de cuántos momentos te quitan el aliento.",textPt:"A vida não é sobre quantas respirações você toma, mas sobre quantos momentos deixam você sem fôlego.",author:"Joyce Meyer"},{text:"Faithfulness is not doing something right once but doing something right over and over.",textEs:"La fidelidad no es hacer algo bien una vez, sino hacer algo bien una y otra vez.",textPt:"A fidelidade não é fazer algo certo uma vez, mas fazer algo certo repetidas vezes.",author:"Joyce Meyer"},{text:"If you look at the world, you'll be distressed. If you look within, you'll be depressed. If you look at God, you'll be at rest.",textEs:"Si miras al mundo, estarás angustiado. Si miras dentro de ti, estarás deprimido. Si miras a Dios, estarás en paz.",textPt:"Se você olhar para o mundo, ficará angustiado. Se olhar para dentro de si, ficará deprimido. Se olhar para Deus, encontrará descanso.",author:"Corrie ten Boom"},{text:"When we work, we work. When we pray, God works.",textEs:"Cuando trabajamos, trabajamos. Cuando oramos, Dios trabaja.",textPt:"Quando nós trabalhamos, nós trabalhamos. Quando oramos, Deus trabalha.",author:"Hudson Taylor"},{text:"A missionary is one who is called by God to leave his home for the sake of others.",textEs:"Un misionero es alguien que es llamado por Dios a dejar su hogar por causa de otros.",textPt:"Um missionário é alguém que é chamado por Deus a deixar seu lar pelos outros.",author:"Hudson Taylor"},{text:"The greatest achievement is not in never falling, but in rising every time you fall.",textEs:"El mayor logro no es nunca caer, sino levantarse cada vez que caes.",textPt:"O maior feito não é nunca cair, mas se levantar sempre que cair.",author:"Brennan Manning"},{text:"All of us are not called to be preachers, but we are all called to be witnesses.",textEs:"No todos somos llamados a ser predicadores, pero todos somos llamados a ser testigos.",textPt:"Nem todos somos chamados a ser pregadores, mas todos somos chamados a ser testemunhas.",author:"Luis Palau"}],t={"Matthew Henry":{"Psalms 23":"David, as a shepherd himself, understood the tender care a shepherd gives his flock. In this psalm he teaches us that the Lord provides for all our needs, leads us in right paths, and protects us even in death's shadow. The table prepared before enemies shows God's provision is not hidden but displayed openly. The overflowing cup speaks of abundance beyond mere sufficiency.","Psalms 91":"This psalm is a covenant of protection for those who dwell in God's presence. The secret place is not a physical location but a state of communion with the Almighty. Every form of danger is addressed: pestilence, terror, arrows, destruction. Angels are commissioned for our safety. God Himself promises to answer, deliver, and satisfy with long life.","Psalms 119":"The longest psalm is entirely devoted to the excellency of God's Word. Every verse references Scripture in some form. The psalmist finds in the Word cleansing for the young, light for the path, comfort in affliction, and delight surpassing riches. This teaches us to hide the Word in our hearts as our greatest treasure.","Proverbs 3":"Solomon instructs his son to trust God completely rather than relying on human reasoning. The promise is that God will direct our paths when we acknowledge Him in all our ways. Honoring God with our firstfruits brings abundance. Even divine discipline should be received as evidence of God's fatherly love toward His children.","Isaiah 40":"After thirty-nine chapters of judgment, Isaiah now speaks comfort to God's people. Their warfare is accomplished, their sin is pardoned. The prophet contrasts the frailty of humanity with the eternal power of God. The crescendo comes in the final verses: those who wait on the Lord will mount up with wings like eagles, finding supernatural strength.","Isaiah 55":"God extends a gracious invitation to every thirsty soul. The offer is free, without money and without price. God reminds us that His thoughts and ways are infinitely higher than ours. His Word goes forth with purpose and always accomplishes what He intends. The chapter closes with creation itself rejoicing as God's people walk in freedom.","Genesis 1":"The creation account establishes God as sovereign over all that exists. Each day builds upon the previous, revealing order, design, and purpose. The repeated phrase 'And God said' shows creation came by divine command. Humanity is the crown of creation, made in God's own image, given dominion and responsibility over all the earth.","Matthew 5":"The Sermon on the Mount opens with the Beatitudes, which reverse worldly values entirely. Those the world considers weak, Christ calls blessed. The poor in spirit inherit the kingdom, the mourners receive comfort, the meek inherit the earth. Christ raises the standard from outward behavior to the condition of the heart itself.","Matthew 6":"Christ teaches that true righteousness is not performed for human applause but directed toward God alone. Giving, prayer, and fasting should be done in secret. The Lord's Prayer provides the model for all prayer. The command to seek first God's kingdom promises that all earthly needs will be supplied when our priorities are rightly ordered.","John 1":"John begins his Gospel with the highest Christology in Scripture. The Word was with God and was God from the beginning. All creation came through Him. The incarnation is the central miracle: the eternal Word became flesh and dwelt among us. John the Baptist bore witness that all might believe through Him.","John 3":"Nicodemus came to Jesus by night, perhaps out of caution, and received the most important teaching on spiritual rebirth. To enter the kingdom one must be born of water and Spirit. The wind blows where it wills, and so the Spirit moves sovereignly. God's love for the world is summarized in the giving of His only Son.","John 14":"On the eve of His crucifixion, Christ comforts His disciples with the promise of heavenly mansions, the assurance that He is the only way to the Father, and the coming of the Holy Spirit as Comforter. He leaves them His peace, which is unlike anything the world offers. Their troubled hearts can rest in His sovereign care.","John 15":"The vine and branches metaphor teaches the absolute necessity of abiding in Christ. Apart from Him we can do nothing of spiritual value. The Father prunes fruitful branches to increase their yield. Obedience to Christ's commandments is the proof of our love for Him, and the result is joy made complete.","Romans 8":"This chapter spans from no condemnation to no separation. The Spirit dwelling in believers gives life, leads them as children of God, and intercedes with groanings too deep for words. Present sufferings cannot compare with coming glory. Nothing in all creation can separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus our Lord.","1 Corinthians 13":"Paul declares that without love, even the most spectacular gifts are worthless. Love is defined not by emotion but by action: patience, kindness, endurance. It bears all things and never fails. Faith and hope are essential, but love is the greatest virtue because it alone endures into eternity when all else passes away.","Ephesians 6":"Paul concludes his letter with the call to spiritual warfare. The armor of God is not optional but necessary against spiritual forces of wickedness. Each piece corresponds to a divine provision: truth as a belt, righteousness as a breastplate, the gospel as shoes, faith as a shield, salvation as a helmet, and the Word as a sword.","Philippians 4":"Writing from prison, Paul demonstrates that joy is not dependent on circumstances. He commands believers to rejoice always and to replace anxiety with prayer accompanied by thanksgiving. The peace of God then guards our hearts and minds. The secret of contentment is found not in having enough but in Christ who strengthens us.","Hebrews 11":"Faith is defined as the substance of things hoped for and the evidence of things not seen. The chapter proceeds to catalog the heroes of faith from Abel to the prophets. Each one acted on what they could not yet see, trusting God's promises. Their examples encourage us to persevere in faith despite present difficulties.","James 1":"James opens with the surprising command to count trials as joy, because testing produces patience and maturity. If we lack wisdom, God gives it generously without reproach. Temptation does not come from God but from our own desires. We must be doers of the Word, not merely hearers who deceive themselves.","Revelation 1":"John receives a vision of the glorified Christ on the island of Patmos. Jesus appears with hair white as wool, eyes like flames, feet like burnished bronze, and a voice like many waters. He holds seven stars in His right hand and declares Himself the First and the Last, the Living One who holds the keys of death and Hades."},"Thayer's":{"Psalms 23":"Key Hebrew — רָעָה (ra'ah, H7462): 'to shepherd, tend, pasture.' Implies active, personal care — not passive ownership. נֶפֶשׁ (nephesh, H5315): 'soul, life, breath.' When God 'restores my soul,' He renews the entire being. צַלְמָוֶת (tsalmaveth, H6757): 'deep shadow, death-shadow.' A compound of tsel (shadow) and maveth (death). גַּם (gam, H1571): 'also, even' — intensifying that even in death's shadow, God is present.","Psalms 91":"Key Hebrew — סֵתֶר (sether, H5643): 'covering, hiding place, secret place.' From sathar, to hide. Indicates intimate, protected communion. צֵל (tsel, H6738): 'shadow' — being so close to God that you are in His shadow. פַּחַד (pachad, H6343): 'dread, terror' — what the one dwelling in God's presence is freed from. שָׂבַע (saba, H7646): 'to satisfy, fill.' God's promise: 'With long life I will satisfy him.'","Psalms 119":"Key Hebrew — תּוֹרָה (torah, H8451): 'instruction, law, teaching.' From yarah, to throw or shoot — God's Word aims straight. עֵדוּת (eduth, H5715): 'testimony, witness.' פִּקּוּדִים (piqqudim, H6490): 'precepts, mandates.' From paqad, to attend to. חֻקִּים (chuqqim, H2706): 'statutes, decrees.' From chaqaq, to engrave — permanent law. מִשְׁפָּטִים (mishpatim, H4941): 'judgments, ordinances.' Righteous rulings.","Proverbs 3":"Key Hebrew — בָּטַח (batach, H982): 'to trust, rely on.' Implies leaning your full weight on something. לֵב (lev, H3820): 'heart, mind, inner man.' The seat of will and intellect, not just emotion. יָשַׁר (yashar, H3474): 'to make straight, direct.' When God 'directs your paths,' He removes crookedness. רְפוּאָה (rephuah, H7500): 'healing, remedy.' Fearing the Lord brings healing to your body.","Isaiah 40":"Key Hebrew — נָחַם (nacham, H5162): 'to comfort, console.' The opening word — God Himself takes the initiative to comfort. קוֹל (qol, H6963): 'voice, sound.' The voice crying in the wilderness. עוּף (uph, H5774): 'to fly, mount up.' Those who wait on God will mount up with wings. קָוָה (qavah, H6960): 'to wait, look eagerly.' Not passive waiting but active, expectant hope — literally to bind together, like twisting a rope.","Isaiah 55":"Key Hebrew — צָמֵא (tsame, H6771): 'thirsty, parched.' God invites every thirsty soul. חִנָּם (chinnam, H2600): 'freely, without cost.' Grace is free — without money, without price. מַחֲשָׁבָה (machashavah, H4284): 'thought, plan, purpose.' God's thoughts are higher than ours. דָּבָר (dabar, H1697): 'word, matter, thing.' God's Word never returns empty — it accomplishes its purpose.","Genesis 1":"Key Hebrew — בָּרָא (bara, H1254): 'to create.' Used exclusively of divine creation — making something fundamentally new. רוּחַ (ruach, H7307): 'spirit, wind, breath.' The Spirit of God hovered over the waters. צֶלֶם (tselem, H6754): 'image, likeness.' Humanity made in God's image. רָדָה (radah, H7287): 'to rule, have dominion.' Stewardship over creation. טוֹב (tov, H2896): 'good.' God declared each day's work 'good' — and humanity 'very good.'","Matthew 5":"Key Greek — μακάριος (makarios, G3107): 'blessed, happy, fortunate.' Not circumstantial happiness but divine blessedness. πτωχός (ptochos, G4434): 'poor, destitute.' In spirit — completely dependent on God. πραΰς (praus, G4239): 'meek, gentle.' Not weakness but strength under control. δικαιοσύνη (dikaiosyne, G1343): 'righteousness.' To hunger and thirst for right standing with God. εἰρηνοποιός (eirenopoios, G1518): 'peacemaker.' One who actively creates peace.","Matthew 6":"Key Greek — ὑποκριτής (hypokrites, G5273): 'hypocrite, play-actor.' One who performs religion for an audience. ταμεῖον (tameion, G5009): 'inner room, storeroom.' Pray in your secret room — intimacy with God. ἐπιούσιος (epiousios, G1967): 'daily.' Give us this day our daily bread — a word found nowhere else in Greek literature. μαμωνᾶς (mamonas, G3126): 'mammon, riches.' You cannot serve both God and mammon. μεριμνάω (merimnao, G3309): 'to be anxious, distracted.' Do not worry about tomorrow.","John 1":"Key Greek — λόγος (logos, G3056): 'word, reason, divine principle.' In the beginning was the Word — Christ as the eternal expression of God. σάρξ (sarx, G4561): 'flesh.' The Word became flesh — the mystery of incarnation. σκηνόω (skenoo, G4637): 'to tabernacle, dwell.' Literally 'pitched His tent among us.' χάρις (charis, G5485): 'grace.' Full of grace and truth. μονογενής (monogenes, G3439): 'only-begotten, unique.' The only-begotten Son.","John 3":"Key Greek — ἄνωθεν (anothen, G509): 'from above, again.' Born again — or born from above. Both meanings are intended. γεννάω (gennao, G1080): 'to beget, give birth to.' Spiritual rebirth by the Spirit. πνεῦμα (pneuma, G4151): 'spirit, wind.' The Spirit blows where He wills — same word for wind and spirit. ὑψόω (hypsoo, G5312): 'to lift up, exalt.' As Moses lifted the serpent, so the Son of Man must be lifted up. ζωή αἰώνιος (zoe aionios, G2222+G166): 'eternal life.' Not just endless duration but divine quality of life.","John 14":"Key Greek — μονή (mone, G3438): 'dwelling place, mansion.' In my Father's house are many dwelling places. ὁδός (hodos, G3598): 'way, road, path.' I am the Way. παράκλητος (parakletos, G3875): 'advocate, helper, comforter.' The Holy Spirit as one called alongside to help. ἀλήθεια (aletheia, G225): 'truth, reality.' I am the Truth. εἰρήνη (eirene, G1515): 'peace.' My peace I give you — not as the world gives.","John 15":"Key Greek — ἄμπελος (ampelos, G288): 'vine, grapevine.' I am the true vine. κλῆμα (klema, G2814): 'branch.' You are the branches. μένω (meno, G3306): 'to abide, remain, dwell.' Abide in me — continuous, ongoing connection. καθαίρω (kathairo, G2508): 'to prune, cleanse.' The Father prunes every fruitful branch. καρπός (karpos, G2590): 'fruit.' Apart from me you can bear no fruit. ἐντολή (entole, G1785): 'commandment.' If you keep my commandments, you abide in my love.","Romans 8":"Key Greek — κατάκριμα (katakrima, G2631): 'condemnation, sentence.' No condemnation for those in Christ. σάρξ (sarx, G4561): 'flesh.' The law of the Spirit vs. the law of the flesh. υἱοθεσία (huiothesia, G5206): 'adoption.' We have received the Spirit of adoption. στεναγμός (stenagmos, G4726): 'groaning.' The Spirit intercedes with groanings too deep for words. χωρίζω (chorizo, G5563): 'to separate.' Nothing can separate us from God's love.","1 Corinthians 13":"Key Greek — ἀγάπη (agape, G26): 'love.' The highest, self-giving love. μακροθυμέω (makrothymeo, G3114): 'to be patient, long-suffering.' Love is patient. χρηστεύομαι (chresteuomai, G5541): 'to be kind.' Love is kind. περπερεύομαι (perpereuomai, G4068): 'to boast, brag.' Love does not boast. τέλειος (teleios, G5046): 'complete, perfect, mature.' When the perfect comes, the partial passes away. The greatest of these is agape.","Ephesians 6":"Key Greek — πανοπλία (panoplia, G3833): 'full armor.' Put on the whole armor of God. πάλη (pale, G3823): 'wrestling.' Our struggle is not against flesh and blood. ἀλήθεια (aletheia, G225): 'truth.' Belt of truth. θώραξ (thorax, G2382): 'breastplate.' Breastplate of righteousness. θυρεός (thyreos, G2375): 'shield.' Shield of faith. μάχαιρα (machaira, G3162): 'sword.' The sword of the Spirit — the Word of God. προσευχή (proseuche, G4335): 'prayer.' Praying at all times in the Spirit.","Philippians 4":"Key Greek — χαίρω (chairo, G5463): 'to rejoice, be glad.' Rejoice in the Lord always. ἐπιεικής (epieikes, G1933): 'gentle, gracious, forbearing.' Let your gentleness be known to all. μεριμνάω (merimnao, G3309): 'to be anxious.' Be anxious for nothing. εὐχαριστία (eucharistia, G2169): 'thanksgiving.' With thanksgiving let your requests be known. αὐτάρκης (autarkes, G842): 'content, self-sufficient.' I have learned to be content — a sufficiency found in Christ, not circumstances.","Hebrews 11":"Key Greek — πίστις (pistis, G4102): 'faith, trust, conviction.' Faith is the substance of things hoped for. ὑπόστασις (hypostasis, G5287): 'substance, confidence, assurance.' The reality beneath what is hoped for. ἔλεγχος (elegchos, G1650): 'evidence, conviction, proof.' The evidence of things not seen. μαρτυρέω (martyreo, G3140): 'to testify, bear witness.' By faith the elders received their testimony. The cloud of witnesses.","James 1":"Key Greek — πειρασμός (peirasmos, G3986): 'trial, testing, temptation.' Count it joy when you face trials. δοκίμιον (dokimion, G1383): 'testing, proving.' The testing of your faith. ὑπομονή (hypomone, G5281): 'endurance, patience, perseverance.' Testing produces endurance. τέλειος (teleios, G5046): 'complete, mature, perfect.' That you may be perfect and complete. δίψυχος (dipsychos, G1374): 'double-minded.' The double-minded man is unstable.","Revelation 1":"Key Greek — ἀποκάλυψις (apokalypsis, G602): 'revelation, unveiling.' The apocalypse — an uncovering of what is hidden. μάρτυς (martys, G3144): 'witness.' Jesus the faithful witness — from which we get 'martyr.' πρωτότοκος (prototokos, G4416): 'firstborn.' The firstborn from the dead. Ἄλφα/Ὦμέγα (Alpha/Omega): The first and last letters of the Greek alphabet — Christ is the beginning and the end. κλείς (kleis, G2807): 'key.' He holds the keys of death and Hades."},"A.W. Tozer":{"Psalms 23":"The shepherd psalm is not merely poetry — it is the testimony of a soul that has discovered the sufficiency of God. When David says the Lord is his shepherd, he is not expressing a theological proposition; he is declaring a lived reality. The green pastures and still waters are not rewards for good behavior but the natural provision of a God who delights in His children. The valley of death's shadow holds no terror for the one who has cultivated the habit of God's presence. The prepared table is worship in the face of opposition. The overflowing cup is the abundant life that flows from intimacy with the living God.","Psalms 91":"The secret place of the Most High is not a location but a condition of the soul. It is the inner sanctuary where the worshiper meets God in spirit and in truth. Those who dwell there — not merely visit — find themselves under the shadow of the Almighty. This is the great privilege of the Spirit-filled life: to abide so closely to God that His very shadow covers you. The dangers listed here are real, but they cannot penetrate the shelter of divine communion. The angels are sent to serve those who are heirs of salvation, and the final promise is God's own voice speaking directly to the beloved soul.","Psalms 119":"Here is a man intoxicated with the Word of God. He does not merely study it — he loves it, delights in it, meditates on it day and night. The modern church has largely lost this consuming passion for Scripture. We read the Bible as we read a textbook, extracting information rather than encountering the living God who speaks through its pages. The psalmist understood that the Word is not merely words about God — it is God speaking. When he says 'Open my eyes,' he acknowledges that without the illumination of the Holy Spirit, even the most diligent reader remains blind to divine truth.","Proverbs 3":"To trust the Lord with all the heart is to make a complete surrender of the understanding to God. The great obstacle to spiritual progress is the habit of leaning on our own intelligence. We are willing to trust God with our eternal destiny but not with our daily decisions. The man who acknowledges God in all his ways has learned the secret of the guided life. He does not demand to see the whole road — he takes the next step in faith. The promise of straight paths is not a guarantee of easy paths, but of right paths. And the discipline of God is the highest expression of His love.","Isaiah 40":"This chapter is the great corrective for every small thought we have ever had about God. The prophet asks: to whom will you compare God? He sits above the circle of the earth. He stretches out the heavens like a curtain. He calls each star by name. The tragedy of the modern church is that we have domesticated this God, made Him manageable, reduced Him to a concept we can fit into our theology. But God will not be contained. He is wholly other, infinitely above us. And yet — this same God bends down to give power to the faint and strength to those who wait upon Him in worship and prayer.","Isaiah 55":"The invitation of God is to every thirsty soul. But the deeper question is: are we thirsty? The great curse of our age is satisfaction with things that cannot satisfy. We have filled our lives with substitutes for God and then wonder why we feel empty. God's thoughts are higher than ours — infinitely, eternally higher. We cannot reach them by climbing; we can only receive them by descending into humility. His Word goes forth with power and purpose, never returning empty. But we must come to it with reverence, expecting to hear the voice of the living God, not merely reading words on a page.","Genesis 1":"In the beginning, God. Before anything else existed, God was. He did not emerge from chaos — He created order out of nothing by the sheer force of His will expressed through His Word. The Spirit brooded over the deep, and when God spoke, creation obeyed. This is the fundamental fact of existence: everything that is, is because God said so. When He created humanity in His image, He stamped us with a dignity that nothing in all creation possesses. We are made for fellowship with the infinite God. The fall shattered that fellowship, but it did not destroy the image. Christ came to restore what was broken.","Matthew 5":"The Beatitudes are not advice for living a better life. They are a description of the character that the Holy Spirit produces in those who have surrendered to Christ. The poor in spirit have come to the end of themselves — and that is exactly where God begins His work. The meek are not the timid but those who have submitted their strength to God. Those who hunger and thirst for righteousness are consumed with a desire that the world cannot understand and cannot satisfy. Only God can fill that void. The pure in heart see God because they have removed every idol that once stood between them and the Almighty.","Matthew 6":"The great indictment of the Pharisees was not that they did wrong things but that they did right things for wrong reasons. The act of worship performed for human approval is not worship at all — it is theater. True prayer is communion with the Father in the secret place, away from the eyes of men. The Lord's Prayer teaches us to begin where God begins: with His name, His kingdom, His will. Our needs come after. The command not to worry is a call to trust the God who feeds the birds and clothes the flowers. If He cares for them, how much more for His children who bear His image?","John 1":"In these opening verses we stand on the highest ground in all of Scripture. The Word was God. Not like God, not similar to God — was God. And this Word, this eternal Logos, became flesh and dwelt among us. The Creator entered His own creation. The infinite became finite. The immortal put on mortality. This is the central mystery of the Christian faith, and we must never allow familiarity to rob it of its wonder. He came to His own, and His own did not receive Him. But to those who did receive Him, He gave the right to become children of God — born not of blood, nor of the will of man, but of God.","John 3":"Nicodemus came to Jesus with knowledge but without life. He knew about God but did not know God. Jesus cuts through all his theology with one devastating statement: you must be born again. This is not reformation, education, or improvement — it is regeneration. The old nature cannot be repaired; it must be replaced. The Spirit moves like the wind — sovereign, unpredictable, beyond human control. We cannot manufacture the new birth any more than we can manufacture the wind. But we can position ourselves to receive it through faith. And the motive behind it all is the incomprehensible love of God for a world that does not deserve it.","John 14":"On the eve of the cross, Jesus speaks words of eternal comfort. Let not your hearts be troubled. He is going to prepare a place. He is the Way — the only way — to the Father. The Holy Spirit, the Comforter, is coming to dwell not with them but in them. This is the great promise of the new covenant: God's presence not in a temple made with hands but within the believer's own spirit. The peace Jesus offers is not the absence of trouble but the presence of God in the middle of trouble. It is wholly different from anything the world can offer or understand.","John 15":"The vine and branches is not an illustration of effort but of dependence. The branch does not strain to produce fruit — it simply remains connected to the vine. All the life, all the nourishment, all the fruitfulness flows from the vine to the branch. Our only task is to abide. And yet this is the hardest thing for the self-reliant human heart to do: to stop striving and simply rest in Christ. The pruning is the Father's work, painful but purposeful. He cuts away everything that hinders deeper communion and greater fruitfulness. The result is joy — the deep, settled joy that comes from union with Christ.","Romans 8":"No condemnation. The believer stands before God with no accusation that can stick. The Spirit of life has broken the power of sin and death. Those who walk in the Spirit — who set their minds on the things above — experience life and peace. The Spirit Himself testifies with our spirits that we are children of God. We are not servants; we are sons and daughters. Present sufferings cannot be compared with the glory to come. The whole creation groans, waiting for the full manifestation of the sons of God. And nothing — no power in heaven, earth, or hell — can separate the redeemed soul from the love of God in Christ Jesus.","1 Corinthians 13":"Paul's hymn to love is placed strategically between two chapters on spiritual gifts. The message is unmistakable: without love, the most spectacular gift is an empty display. You may speak in the tongues of angels, but without love it is noise. You may have prophetic insight, mountain-moving faith, sacrificial generosity — but without love, you gain nothing. Love is patient when everything within you wants to react. It is kind when cruelty would be easier. It does not envy, boast, or keep accounts of wrongs. When all the gifts have served their purpose and passed away, three things remain: faith, hope, and love. And the greatest is love.","Ephesians 6":"The Christian life is lived on a battlefield, not a playground. Paul pulls back the curtain to reveal the true nature of our conflict: not against flesh and blood but against spiritual powers of wickedness in the heavenly places. The armor of God is essential, not optional. Truth protects against the father of lies. Righteousness guards the heart against accusation. The gospel gives firm footing on shifting ground. Faith extinguishes the enemy's flaming arrows. The helmet of salvation guards the mind. And the sword of the Spirit — the living Word of God — is our only offensive weapon. All of this is activated and sustained through prayer in the Spirit.","Philippians 4":"Joy written from a prison cell. This alone tells us that Paul had discovered something the world desperately needs: that joy is not dependent on circumstances but on the unchanging character of God. Rejoice always — not sometimes, always. When anxiety comes, the remedy is not willpower but prayer saturated with thanksgiving. The peace that follows is supernatural — it surpasses human understanding and stands guard over the heart and mind. The secret of contentment is not having what you want but wanting what you have in Christ. I can do all things through Him who pours His strength into me.","Hebrews 11":"Faith is the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen. It is not wishful thinking but rock-solid confidence in the character of God. Every hero in this chapter took God at His Word and acted before seeing the result. Abel offered. Noah built. Abraham journeyed. Moses refused the pleasures of Egypt. They were all looking beyond the visible to the invisible, beyond the temporal to the eternal. They did not receive the fulfillment of the promises in their lifetime, but they never stopped believing. They were strangers and pilgrims, seeking a homeland — a city whose architect and builder is God Himself.","James 1":"Count it all joy when trials come. Not some joy — all joy. James understood something that the comfortable church often misses: trials are not obstacles to faith; they are the proving ground of faith. The testing produces endurance, and endurance produces maturity. If you lack wisdom in the furnace of affliction, ask God — and He gives generously without shaming you for asking. But you must ask in faith, without the double-mindedness that tries to trust God and lean on human wisdom at the same time. Every good gift descends from the Father of lights, in whom there is no shadow of turning.","Revelation 1":"The Revelation is exactly that — an unveiling. Not of coming events primarily, but of Jesus Christ Himself in His risen, glorified, triumphant majesty. John was in the Spirit — caught up in divine communion — when he heard the voice like a trumpet. He turned and saw Christ standing among the lampstands, which are the churches. His eyes like fire see everything. His voice like many waters carries absolute authority. The sword from His mouth is His Word that judges and divides. When John fell as dead, Jesus laid His hand on him and spoke: Do not fear. I am the First and the Last, the Living One who conquered death itself."},Wigglesworth:{"Psalms 23":"God is not stingy with His provision. The Lord is your Shepherd — that settles the matter. He makes you lie down in green pastures because He knows you need rest even when you think you do not. He restores your soul — spirit, mind, and body — because He is a God of complete restoration. I have seen God restore bodies that doctors gave up on, minds that were tormented, and spirits that were crushed. The valley of death's shadow holds no fear for the Spirit-filled believer. A shadow never killed anyone. Walk through it boldly. God has prepared a table for you, and the enemy has to watch you feast.","Psalms 91":"I have lived in this psalm. When you make the Most High your dwelling place — not just a Sunday visit but your permanent address — you come under protection that no devil in hell can penetrate. I have walked into rooms where people were dying of plague, and the plague could not touch me because I was hidden in the secret place. A thousand may fall at your side, but it will not come near you. This is not theory — this is the covenant promise of God to those who dwell in His presence. Angels are real, their protection is real, and God's promise to deliver is real.","Psalms 119":"The Word of God is not a dead book. It is alive with the power of the Holy Spirit. When you take the Word into your spirit, it becomes life and health and strength. The psalmist loved God's Word more than gold, more than food — and that is the kind of hunger that moves heaven. I have seen God's Word heal the sick, cast out demons, and set captives free. Not because of clever theology, but because the Word carries the very power and authority of God. Hide it in your heart. Speak it with your mouth. The Word of God in the mouth of a believing man or woman is the most powerful force on earth.","Proverbs 3":"Trust in the Lord — not in your feelings, not in your circumstances, not in what people tell you. Trust Him with everything. When God says He will direct your paths, He means it. I have seen God open doors that no man could open and close doors that no man could close. He knows the way you should go even when you cannot see two steps ahead. The fear of the Lord is the beginning of all wisdom, and honoring God with your substance releases a river of provision. God is no man's debtor. Give to Him and watch what He does in return.","Isaiah 40":"Have you not known? Have you not heard? The everlasting God does not faint or grow weary. If that is true of God, then it can be true of you when His Spirit fills you. I have preached when my body was exhausted, and the Holy Spirit gave me strength I did not have in the natural. Those who wait on the Lord renew their strength. They mount up with wings like eagles. This is not poetry — this is a description of what happens when a Spirit-filled believer connects with the power of the Almighty. You will run and not be weary. You will walk and not faint. God's strength is made perfect in your weakness.","Isaiah 55":"Come, everyone who is thirsty. God does not say come when you are worthy — He says come when you are thirsty. The invitation is to those who know they need something they cannot provide for themselves. God's Word will not return empty. I have spoken God's Word over the sick and watched diseases leave. I have declared God's promises over impossible situations and seen them turn around. The Word of God is creative power. When God speaks, things happen. And when you speak His Word in faith, by the power of the Holy Spirit, the same creative force is released through you.","Genesis 1":"God created everything by His Word, and the Spirit of God was moving over the face of the waters. Word and Spirit together — that is how God works, and that is how He works through us. When God said let there be light, light came. When He made man in His own image, He breathed His own life into him. That breath is the same Holy Spirit who raised Christ from the dead and now lives in every born-again believer. You are not just a creation — you are a carrier of divine life. The same Spirit that hovered over the chaos at creation hovers over your situation right now, ready to bring order and life.","Matthew 5":"Blessed are the poor in spirit — those who know they have nothing without God. That is the starting place for everything the Holy Spirit wants to do in your life. The meek are not the weak — they are those whose strength is submitted to God. I have seen the meekest saints exercise the greatest power because they had nothing to prove and everything to give. The pure in heart see God — not with physical eyes but with the eyes of the Spirit. When your heart is clean, the Holy Spirit moves through you without hindrance. You become a channel of His power, His love, His miracles.","Matthew 6":"Do not do your works to be seen by men. God sees in secret, and He rewards in secret. I have found that the most powerful prayers are not the longest or the loudest — they are the ones prayed in the secret place where only God can hear. The Lord's Prayer teaches us to put God's kingdom first. When you seek His kingdom and His righteousness above everything else, He takes care of the rest. Do not worry — worry is faith in the wrong direction. It is believing that the problem is bigger than God. Cast your care on Him. He is well able to handle whatever you are facing.","John 1":"The Word was God. This is the foundation of everything. Jesus is not just a teacher or a prophet — He is God in the flesh. Everything that was made was made through Him. And when the Word became flesh, heaven invaded earth. The power that created the universe walked among us. I have seen that same power heal the blind, raise the crippled, and deliver the tormented. It is the same Word, the same Jesus, the same power. He is full of grace and truth. Not grace alone and not truth alone — both together. That is the balance of the Spirit-filled life: tender in mercy and uncompromising in truth.","John 3":"You must be born again. Not educated again, not reformed again — born again. The Spirit gives birth to spirit. This is a supernatural work that no human effort can produce. The wind blows where it wills — you hear its sound but cannot tell where it comes from or where it is going. The Holy Spirit moves the same way. You cannot control Him, but you can yield to Him. When Nicodemus struggled to understand, Jesus pointed him to the cross: as Moses lifted up the serpent, so the Son of Man must be lifted up. Look to Jesus and live. That is the simplest and most powerful message in the world.","John 14":"Let not your heart be troubled. Jesus speaks these words to frightened disciples, and He speaks them to you today. He has gone to prepare a place for you — and He is coming back. He is the Way, the Truth, and the Life. There is no other way to the Father. But here is the word that sets the Spirit-filled believer on fire: greater works than these shall you do, because I go to the Father. The Holy Spirit — the Comforter, the Helper, the Spirit of Truth — is coming to live inside you. Not just with you, but in you. That changes everything. His peace is not like the world's peace. It is supernatural, unshakeable, and alive.","John 15":"Abide in Me. Stay connected. Do not go wandering off on your own. The branch that stays connected to the vine bears fruit naturally — it does not have to strain or struggle. Your job is to stay close to Jesus through prayer, through His Word, and through obedience. The Father prunes the fruitful branch — and pruning hurts. But it is always for the purpose of greater fruitfulness. I have been pruned many times, and every time God cut something away, He released more of His power through me. Apart from Him you can do nothing. But connected to Him, there is nothing you cannot do.","Romans 8":"There is no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus. The law of the Spirit of life has set you free. Do you understand what this means? You are free. Free from sin's dominion, free from death's grip, free from the enemy's accusations. The Spirit of God lives in you — the same Spirit that raised Jesus from the dead. If that Spirit dwells in you, He will give life to your mortal body. You are not a slave to fear — you are a child of God. The Spirit bears witness with your spirit. Present sufferings are nothing compared to the glory coming. And nothing — nothing — can separate you from His love.","1 Corinthians 13":"I have seen every gift of the Spirit in operation. I have spoken in tongues, interpreted, prophesied, seen words of knowledge and wisdom, witnessed miracles and healings. But Paul says all of it is nothing without love. Nothing. You can have the most spectacular gifts and be bankrupt without love. Love is patient when everything in you wants to fight. Love is kind when cruelty would be easier. Love does not keep score. Love never fails. The gifts will pass away when we see Him face to face. But love endures forever because God is love, and those who abide in love abide in God.","Ephesians 6":"We wrestle not against flesh and blood. The devil is real, demons are real, and the spiritual battle is real. But so is the armor of God. Put it on — all of it. Truth as your belt, righteousness as your breastplate, the gospel of peace on your feet, faith as your shield, salvation as your helmet, and the Word of God as your sword. I have faced down demons with the Word of God and watched them flee. The enemy has no defense against a Spirit-filled believer who knows the Word and wields it in faith. And pray — pray in the Spirit at all times. Prayer is the atmosphere of victory.","Philippians 4":"Rejoice in the Lord always. Paul wrote this from prison. He was not in comfortable circumstances — he was in chains. But his joy was not in his circumstances; it was in his God. When anxiety comes, pray. Not just any prayer — pray with thanksgiving. Thank God in the middle of the problem, and watch what happens. The peace of God will guard your heart like a soldier on duty. I can do all things through Christ who strengthens me. This is not positive thinking — this is Holy Spirit power. Paul had learned that in any situation — abundance or need, freedom or prison — Christ was enough.","Hebrews 11":"Faith is the substance of things hoped for. Not a wish, not a feeling — substance. Real, tangible, spiritual substance. By faith Abel offered. By faith Noah built. By faith Abraham left everything he knew. By faith Sarah conceived when it was physically impossible. These men and women took God at His Word and acted before they saw the result. That is faith. I have prayed for the dead and seen them raised because I believed God's Word more than I believed what my eyes told me. The heroes of faith did not receive the promise in their lifetime, but they never stopped believing. That is the faith that pleases God.","James 1":"Count it all joy. All joy. Not some joy when things go well — all joy when trials come. Because trials test your faith, and tested faith produces endurance, and endurance produces completeness. You cannot be made complete without being tested. If you lack wisdom, ask God. He gives it freely, generously, without shaming you for needing it. But ask in faith. Do not be double-minded — half believing, half doubting. A double-minded man receives nothing from God. Every good gift comes from above, from the Father who does not change. He is the same yesterday, today, and forever. Trust Him completely.","Revelation 1":"This is the revelation of Jesus Christ — not the revelation of coming doom, but the revelation of who Jesus really is. John was in the Spirit. That is the key to seeing Jesus as He truly is — you must be in the Spirit. When John turned, he saw the glorified Christ: eyes like fire, voice like many waters, a sharp sword from His mouth. This is not the gentle Jesus of the Sunday school pictures — this is the King of Kings and Lord of Lords in His full glory and power. When John fell as dead, Jesus touched him and said: Do not be afraid. I hold the keys of death and hell. Every enemy is defeated."},"Teachers (Structure)":{"Psalms 23":"This psalm serves as a teaching model for understanding God's pastoral care. The shepherd metaphor was deeply meaningful to an agricultural society. Students of Scripture should note the progression: provision (green pastures), guidance (right paths), protection (valley of death), and celebration (prepared table). Each image builds confidence in God's comprehensive care for His people.","Psalms 91":"For teaching purposes, Psalm 91 addresses four categories of danger: hidden traps (snare of the fowler), disease (pestilence), warfare (arrows by day), and supernatural evil (terror by night). The psalm teaches that divine protection is conditional on dwelling in the secret place. The angelic ministry described here was quoted by Satan during Christ's temptation.","Psalms 119":"This acrostic psalm is structured around the Hebrew alphabet, with eight verses per letter. It uses eight different terms for Scripture: law, testimonies, precepts, statutes, commandments, judgments, word, and ordinances. Each term reveals a different facet of how God communicates with humanity. This structure makes it an ideal teaching text for the nature of Scripture.","Proverbs 3":"The teaching emphasis in Proverbs 3 centers on the relationship between trust and understanding. Verse 5 establishes the foundational principle: trust must be wholehearted, and human understanding must not be the final authority. The practical applications follow logically: acknowledge God in all decisions, honor Him with resources, accept His correction as a form of love.","Isaiah 40":"Isaiah 40 serves as a bridge between the first and second halves of Isaiah. The literary structure moves from comfort to proclamation to theological reflection. Key teaching points include the temporary nature of human accomplishments compared to God's eternal Word, the incomparability of God to any created thing, and the renewing power available to those who wait on Him.","Isaiah 55":"This chapter is structured as a divine invitation in three movements: the call to come, the call to seek, and the promise of God's effective Word. Key teaching insight: God's ways are higher than ours not in degree but in kind. The rain metaphor for God's Word teaches that Scripture always accomplishes its intended purpose and never returns empty.","Genesis 1":"Genesis 1 establishes foundational doctrines: the existence of God prior to creation, creation by divine speech, the ordered nature of the universe, the special creation of humanity in God's image, and the goodness of the material world. The six-day structure with a seventh day of rest establishes the theological basis for sabbath observance.","Matthew 5":"The Beatitudes function as the constitution of Christ's kingdom. Each beatitude follows a pattern: condition, then promise. Teaching insight: the qualities described are not natural human virtues but spiritual characteristics produced by the Holy Spirit. They are sequential, building upon each other from poverty of spirit to persecution for righteousness.","Matthew 6":"Chapter 6 contrasts genuine devotion with religious performance. The three practices examined (giving, prayer, fasting) were the pillars of Jewish piety. Jesus does not condemn the practices but the motivation behind them. The Lord's Prayer provides a six-part model covering worship, submission, provision, forgiveness, guidance, and deliverance.","John 1":"John's prologue establishes the pre-existence, deity, and creative agency of Christ. The term Logos (Word) bridges Hebrew and Greek thought, presenting Jesus as both the divine speech of God and the rational principle behind creation. Teaching point: the progression from creation to incarnation to revelation shows God's relentless movement toward humanity.","John 3":"The dialogue with Nicodemus is structured around three misunderstandings, each deepening the teaching. Born again can also mean born from above. Water and Spirit may reference baptism, natural birth, or Old Testament purification. The wind metaphor teaches the sovereignty and mystery of the Spirit's work. John 3:16 summarizes substitutionary atonement.","John 14":"This farewell discourse addresses four concerns of the disciples: where Jesus is going, how to get there, what the Father is like, and who will help them after Jesus leaves. The answers reveal Jesus as the preparer of heaven, the exclusive way to God, the perfect image of the Father, and the sender of the Holy Spirit.","John 15":"The vine metaphor teaches three types of branches: fruitless (removed), fruitful (pruned), and abiding (bearing much fruit). Teaching insight: pruning is not punishment but preparation for greater fruitfulness. The shift from vine imagery to friendship language shows progression from duty to intimacy. Love is both the means and the evidence of abiding.","Romans 8":"Romans 8 can be taught in four movements: freedom from condemnation (1-4), life in the Spirit (5-17), hope in suffering (18-30), and security in God's love (31-39). The golden chain of salvation in verses 29-30 connects foreknowledge, predestination, calling, justification, and glorification as one unbreakable sequence.","1 Corinthians 13":"Paul places this chapter between chapters 12 and 14, which discuss spiritual gifts. This placement is intentional: love is the context in which all gifts must operate. The fifteen qualities of love in verses 4-7 can be taught as a diagnostic checklist for measuring spiritual maturity. The contrast between partial and complete knowledge points to the eternal nature of love.","Ephesians 6":"The armor of God passage uses Roman military equipment as an extended metaphor. Each piece is both defensive and connected to a spiritual reality. Teaching insight: the armor is described for standing, not advancing, suggesting that the primary posture of spiritual warfare is firm resistance. Prayer in verse 18 is not a separate piece but the atmosphere in which the armor functions.","Philippians 4":"Paul models contentment as a learned skill, not a natural disposition. The peace of God (verse 7) and the God of peace (verse 9) are distinct concepts: one guards our minds, the other accompanies our obedience. The list of virtues in verse 8 provides a mental discipline framework. Paul's contentment came through Christ's strength, not self-sufficiency.","Hebrews 11":"The faith chapter functions as a gallery of examples illustrating the definition in verse 1. Each hero demonstrates a different aspect of faith: Abel (worship), Enoch (walk), Noah (work), Abraham (obedience), Sarah (impossibility), Moses (choice). The progression shows faith operating in increasingly difficult circumstances, teaching that faith grows through testing.","James 1":"James structures his opening around the testing-wisdom-temptation cycle. Testing produces endurance; endurance requires wisdom; wisdom is freely given by God. The critical teaching distinction is between testing (from God, for growth) and temptation (from desire, leading to sin). The mirror metaphor (verses 23-25) powerfully illustrates the difference between hearing and doing.","Revelation 1":"The opening vision establishes Christ's authority over the churches. Each element of His appearance connects to Old Testament imagery: the white hair to Daniel 7, the bronze feet to Daniel 10, the sharp sword to Isaiah 49. The seven lampstands represent the seven churches, and the seven stars their messengers. Christ walks among His churches as overseer and judge."},Spurgeon:{"Psalms 23":"What condescension is this, that the infinite Lord assumes the office of a Shepherd! The Lord is my shepherd — not merely a shepherd to others, but to me. He makes me lie down, for He knows that rest is needful. He leads beside still waters, not rushing torrents that would overwhelm. This is the psalm that has dried more tears and quieted more fears than any other song in the whole Word of God.","Psalms 91":"Here is a most precious promise for every soul that has learned to dwell in the secret place. The fowler sets his traps in secret, but God who sees all secrets delivers us. Under His wings! What a picture of tender, brooding, sheltering love. A thousand may fall at your side, ten thousand at your right hand, but the promise stands: it shall not come near you.","Psalms 119":"The psalm is all about the Word of God, and yet it is addressed to the God of the Word. This is the key to its power. The psalmist does not merely study Scripture; he speaks to its Author. Every petition rises from the page to the throne. To hide God's Word in the heart is the best preservative against sin that a believer can ever possess.","Proverbs 3":"Trust in the Lord with all thine heart! Not with half thy heart, not with a corner of thy heart, but with all of it. Lean not on thine own understanding — for our understanding is a broken reed that will pierce the hand that rests upon it. Acknowledge Him in all thy ways: in the little things and the great, in the joys and the sorrows, and He shall direct thy paths.","Isaiah 40":"Comfort ye! What music in those words. God does not say 'Condemn ye my people,' but 'Comfort ye.' The grass withers, the flower fades, but the Word of our God stands forever. Here is the rock beneath our feet while all else shifts like sand. And then that glorious climax: they that wait upon the Lord shall mount up with wings as eagles. What soaring! What freedom!","Isaiah 55":"Ho, every one that thirsteth! God does not whisper this invitation; He cries it aloud. Come to the waters! It is free, without money and without price. My ways are higher than your ways, says the Lord. So when you cannot understand His dealings, remember that His thoughts are as far above yours as the heavens are above the earth. Trust where you cannot trace.","Genesis 1":"In the beginning God. Four words that settle every question of philosophy and science. God created — He did not improve upon existing material; He spoke into nothing and something appeared. Let there be light — and there was light. The same God who commanded light from darkness can speak light into the darkest soul. His creative power is matched by His redemptive power.","Matthew 5":"Blessed are the poor in spirit! The kingdom belongs not to the proud and self-sufficient but to those who know their spiritual bankruptcy. Christ begins His kingdom manifesto not with commands but with blessings. Each beatitude is a diamond, and together they form a crown that only grace can place upon the head of the humblest believer.","Matthew 6":"When thou prayest, enter into thy closet. Secret prayer is the secret of prayer. The closet of prayer is the most important room in the house. Our Father — what tenderness! Hallowed be Thy name — what reverence! Give us our daily bread — what dependence! Forgive us — what humility! Every petition in this prayer is a treasury of theology.","John 1":"In the beginning was the Word. Not 'in the beginning the Word was created,' but 'the Word was.' He had no beginning. He was with God and He was God. All things were made by Him. The same hands that flung stars into space would later be nailed to a cross. This is the mystery that angels desire to look into.","John 3":"Ye must be born again. There is no softening of this declaration, no exception clause. A ruler of Israel, moral and religious, is told that all his attainment counts for nothing without new birth. The wind blows where it wishes — so the Spirit moves with sovereign freedom. And then, the golden text: God so loved the world that He gave.","John 14":"Let not your heart be troubled. How like the Savior to think of His disciples' sorrow even as He faces His own cross. I go to prepare a place for you. Heaven is not merely a state but a place, prepared by a Person who loves us. I am the way — not a way among many, but the way, the only way to the Father.","John 15":"I am the vine, ye are the branches. Apart from me ye can do nothing. Not 'very little,' not 'something with great difficulty,' but nothing. The branch has no life of its own. Cut it from the vine and it withers. So the Christian who does not abide in Christ will produce no lasting fruit. Abide in me — this is both the command and the invitation.","Romans 8":"No condemnation! What a way to begin a chapter. And no separation — what a way to end one. Between these two mountain peaks stretches the richest valley of truth in all Scripture. The Spirit helps our infirmity. All things work together for good. If God be for us, who can be against us? Neither death nor life can separate us from His love.","1 Corinthians 13":"Though I speak with the tongues of men and of angels — suppose I had all eloquence — and have not love, I am nothing but noise. Love suffers long and is kind. It does not parade itself. It bears all things. Love never fails. Prophecies will cease, tongues will be silenced, knowledge will pass away. But love remains. It is the eternal virtue.","Ephesians 6":"Put on the whole armor of God — the whole armor, not part of it. The soldier who leaves one piece behind exposes himself to the enemy. We wrestle not against flesh and blood. Our battle is spiritual, and only spiritual armor will prevail. Take the sword of the Spirit, which is the Word of God. It is both our weapon and our light.","Philippians 4":"Rejoice in the Lord always, and again I say, Rejoice! This is not the command of a man at ease but of a prisoner in chains. Paul had learned the secret of contentment. I can do all things through Christ who strengthens me. Not some things, not easy things, but all things. The strength is not our own but His, flowing through us like sap through the vine.","Hebrews 11":"Faith is the substance of things hoped for. Not a vague wish, not a fond dream, but substance — real, solid, tangible confidence in God's promise. By faith Abel offered, by faith Noah built, by faith Abraham obeyed. The common thread is this: each one acted on what God said before they saw what God would do. This is the essence of faith.","James 1":"Count it all joy! Not some joy, not partial joy, but all joy when you fall into trials. The trying of your faith produces patience. God is doing a work in you through the trial. If you lack wisdom, ask — and God gives generously without finding fault. What a generous God we serve! He does not rebuke us for asking but delights in our dependence.","Revelation 1":"Fear not! The risen Christ speaks to John lying prostrate before Him. I am the First and the Last. I am He that lives, and was dead, and behold, I am alive forevermore. The keys of death and hell hang at His belt. The churches are in His hand. Every pastor, every believer, is held in the grip of the glorified Christ who walks among His people."},Wesley:{"Psalms 23":"The Lord shepherds His people not merely to save them from danger but to lead them into fullness of life. The green pastures represent the nourishment of grace, the still waters the peace of a sanctified heart. Even in the valley we need not fear, for the Shepherd walks with us. His goodness follows us, pursuing us with mercy until we dwell with Him eternally.","Psalms 91":"This psalm promises extraordinary protection to those who make the Lord their habitation. The practical application is this: our safety depends not on circumstance but on our spiritual position. Those who dwell in the secret place — who maintain constant communion with God — find themselves under divine protection that no earthly power can penetrate.","Psalms 119":"The love for God's Word expressed here is not mere intellectual appreciation but the passion of a heart being sanctified. The psalmist asks God to open his eyes, teach his statutes, and quicken him according to the Word. This teaches us that Scripture is the primary instrument of sanctification, transforming us from glory to glory as we meditate upon it.","Proverbs 3":"The call to trust with all the heart means a complete surrender of our will to God's wisdom. We are not to rely on our own reasoning, which is corrupted by self-interest and limited perspective. When we acknowledge God in every decision, He straightens our path. Honoring God with our resources is not a transaction but an expression of a consecrated life.","Isaiah 40":"God comforts His people by revealing His incomparable greatness. The nations are as a drop in the bucket before Him. No one can counsel Him or add to His understanding. Yet this infinitely powerful God stoops to give strength to the faint. The waiting spoken of is not passive idleness but active, expectant trust that God will renew our strength for service.","Isaiah 55":"God invites every seeking soul to come freely to the waters of grace. The critical insight is that God's ways are higher than ours — not merely in degree but in kind. We must abandon our own thoughts and ways, turning fully to the Lord. His Word goes forth with purpose and power, accomplishing exactly what He intends in every heart that receives it.","Genesis 1":"Creation reveals both God's power and His orderly design. Each day builds upon the previous, showing that God works methodically toward His purposes. The creation of humanity in God's image establishes our unique dignity and responsibility. We are made for relationship with God and stewardship of His creation, a calling that sin has marred but grace restores.","Matthew 5":"The Beatitudes describe the character of those who are being transformed by grace. Poverty of spirit is the starting point of all spiritual growth, for only those who recognize their emptiness can be filled. Each quality builds upon the last, producing people who hunger for righteousness, show mercy, pursue peace, and willingly suffer for the sake of Christ's kingdom.","Matthew 6":"Christ teaches that the heart's orientation determines the value of every religious act. Giving, praying, and fasting done for human approval have already received their full reward. The Lord's Prayer teaches us to begin with God's glory, submit to His will, depend on His provision, seek His forgiveness, and trust His protection. Seeking His kingdom first orders everything else.","John 1":"The Word was God — this establishes the full deity of Christ. All things were made through Him — this establishes His creative power. The Word became flesh — this establishes the incarnation. In this progression we see the heart of the gospel: the God who made us became one of us to redeem us. Grace and truth came through Jesus Christ.","John 3":"The new birth is not reformation but regeneration. Nicodemus, with all his learning and morality, needed to be born again. This teaching overturns every system of salvation by human effort. The Spirit moves with sovereign freedom, like the wind. And the motive behind it all is love: God so loved the world that He gave His only Son.","John 14":"Christ's words to His troubled disciples reveal the heart of pastoral care. He does not explain away their sorrow but points them to a greater reality: the Father's house, the prepared place, the coming reunion. The way to the Father is not through religious systems but through Christ alone. The Holy Spirit continues Christ's ministry of teaching, comforting, and guiding.","John 15":"Abiding in Christ is the secret of all fruitfulness. The branch produces fruit not by its own effort but by remaining connected to the vine. Pruning is painful but purposeful — it removes what hinders greater fruitfulness. The proof of our love for Christ is obedience to His commands. The result of abiding is not mere duty but complete, overflowing joy.","Romans 8":"The Spirit of life sets us free from the law of sin and death. Those who walk according to the Spirit experience life and peace. The Spirit Himself bears witness that we are children of God. Present sufferings are not worthy to be compared with the coming glory. And nothing — absolutely nothing — can separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus.","1 Corinthians 13":"Love is the fulfillment of the law and the evidence of genuine spiritual life. Without love, the most impressive gifts are empty performance. Love is defined by action, not emotion: it is patient, kind, not envious, not proud. It endures all things. When all else passes away, love remains. It is the greatest virtue because it most closely reflects God's own nature.","Ephesians 6":"The call to put on God's armor is a call to active holiness. Each piece represents a grace that must be deliberately embraced. Truth guards against deception, righteousness against accusation, the gospel against instability, faith against doubt, salvation against despair, and the Word against error. Prayer is the atmosphere in which the whole armor becomes effective.","Philippians 4":"Paul's joy in prison demonstrates that circumstances need not determine our spiritual state. Rejoicing is a choice enabled by the Spirit. Anxiety is overcome not by willpower but by prayer with thanksgiving. The peace of God then acts as a garrison around our hearts. Contentment is a learned grace, available to all who draw their strength from Christ.","Hebrews 11":"Faith is not wishful thinking but confident trust in God's revealed character and promises. Each hero of faith acted on what God said before seeing the fulfillment. Abel worshiped, Noah built, Abraham journeyed, Moses chose suffering over comfort. Their faith was not passive belief but active obedience. They looked beyond the visible to the eternal city whose builder is God.","James 1":"Trials are not punishments but instruments of growth. The testing of faith produces endurance, and endurance leads to spiritual completeness. When wisdom is needed, God gives generously to all who ask in faith. The critical distinction between testing and temptation preserves God's character: He tests to strengthen but never tempts to destroy. We must be doers of the Word, not hearers only.","Revelation 1":"The glorified Christ is revealed in power and majesty. John falls at His feet as dead, overwhelmed by the vision. Yet Christ's first word is comfort: Fear not. He identifies Himself as the one who was dead and is now alive forever. He holds the keys of death and the grave. This vision assures every struggling church that Christ walks among them as sovereign Lord."},"Teachers (Application)":{"Psalms 23":"Application question: When have you experienced God as your shepherd — providing when you were in lack, restoring when you were depleted, guiding when you were lost? The 'table prepared before enemies' is not just provision; it is public provision — God honoring you in the very context where you have been diminished. Journaling prompt: Where are you walking through a valley right now, and what does it mean practically to 'fear no evil' in that space?","Psalms 91":"Teaching note: Verse 14 shifts to God's first-person voice — 'Because he loves me,' God says, 'I will rescue him.' The condition is not perfection but love. The protection described here is covenant protection — available to those who have entered relationship with God. Discussion question: What is the difference between 'visiting' God in difficulty versus 'dwelling' in His presence as a daily posture?","Psalms 119":"Structural note: The psalm has 176 verses organized in 22 sections of 8 verses each, each section beginning with a successive letter of the Hebrew alphabet. The psalmist uses at least 8 different words for Scripture throughout — Torah, statutes, precepts, commands, decrees, laws, word, ordinances. What does the variety of terms tell us about the psalmist's view of God's Word?","Proverbs 3":"Three pairs dominate this passage: (1) trust vs. lean on your own understanding, (2) acknowledge vs. be wise in your own eyes, (3) honor God vs. withhold what is due. Each pair presents the same underlying choice: self-reliance or God-dependence. Application: In which of these three areas do you most struggle to practice dependence on God?","Isaiah 40":"Historical context: This passage was written to a nation about to go into exile — or, prophetically, already in it. The comfort of God comes precisely into circumstances that seem to contradict His power and care. 'Why do you say, O Jacob, that God doesn't see your way?' God hears that accusation and responds not with rebuke but with a vision of His greatness. Teaching point: Spiritual exhaustion is real, and God's response is not condemnation but renewal.","Isaiah 55":"The invitation here is radically free and radically inclusive: 'everyone who thirsts.' The Hebrew word (tsame) carries urgency — parched, desperately thirsty. God does not wait for us to clean up before inviting us. Application: What substitutes have you been drinking from that can't satisfy? The call to 'return to the Lord' is not a call to earn His favor but to receive the compassion He is ready to give abundantly.","Genesis 1":"Theological note: The creation account emphasizes order, intention, and goodness. Each stage builds on the previous. The repeated phrase 'God saw that it was good' culminates in 'very good' when humanity is created. Discussion question: What does being made in God's image (imago Dei) mean for how we view ourselves, other people, and the natural world?","Matthew 5":"Teaching structure: The Beatitudes are not commands but descriptions — Jesus describes the character of Kingdom citizens. The movement is from poverty of spirit (acknowledging need) to persecution (enduring cost). Application: Which beatitude challenges you most? Which describes where you currently are in your spiritual journey?","Matthew 6":"Threefold pattern: Jesus addresses three religious practices — giving (vv.1-4), prayer (vv.5-15), and fasting (vv.16-18) — with the same structure: don't do it to be seen by others; do it in secret; your Father who sees in secret will reward you. The principle is not about hiding faith but about who your faith is aimed at. Discussion: What does it mean for your 'audience of One' to be God rather than others?","John 1":"Prologue structure: John 1:1-18 functions as an overture to the whole Gospel, introducing major themes — light/darkness, Word, grace, truth, belief, witness, world. The incarnation ('the Word became flesh') is the pivot point. Teaching application: How does understanding Jesus as the eternal Word change how you read the Gospels — not just as history but as the Word of God speaking in person?","John 3":"Nicodemus conversation outline: (1) Nicodemus initiates with acknowledgment (v.2), (2) Jesus redirects to the core need — new birth (v.3), (3) Nicodemus misunderstands literally (v.4), (4) Jesus explains the spiritual reality (vv.5-8), (5) Nicodemus remains confused (v.9), (6) Jesus expands to the cosmic scope of God's love (vv.10-17). Note: John 3:16 is not a stand-alone verse — it is the conclusion of a conversation about spiritual transformation.","John 14":"Pastoral application: Jesus addresses 'troubled hearts' directly. The word (tarasso) means deeply agitated, stirred up, disturbed. The remedy is not an explanation but a command: 'Trust in God; trust also in me.' Three gifts in this chapter: (1) a prepared place (v.2), (2) a clear way (v.6), (3) an abiding Helper (vv.16-17). Discussion: Which of these three gifts do you most need to receive today?","John 15":"Horticultural note: Grapevines were cultivated throughout Israel — every listener understood pruning. The vinedresser cuts both dead branches (bearing no fruit) and living branches (bearing some fruit) — the goal is maximum fruitfulness. Teaching point: Pruning is evidence of belonging, not rejection. The pain of pruning comes precisely because the branch is connected and alive. Application: What in your life might be a pruning season rather than an abandonment?","Romans 8":"Structural map of the chapter: vv.1-4 (no condemnation), vv.5-11 (Spirit vs. flesh), vv.12-17 (children of God), vv.18-25 (future glory), vv.26-27 (Spirit's intercession), vv.28-30 (sovereign purpose), vv.31-39 (unbreakable love). The chapter begins with 'no condemnation' and ends with 'nothing can separate us' — the believer is secure on both ends. Discussion: Which section of Romans 8 speaks most to where you are right now?","1 Corinthians 13":"Context note: Chapter 12 celebrates spiritual gifts; chapter 14 regulates their use. Chapter 13 is placed deliberately in between to establish love as the governing principle. Without love, gifts become performance and can harm community. Teaching: Paul does not say gifts are bad — he says they are incomplete without love. Application: How would your use of your gifts change if love (not impact, not recognition) were the sole criterion?","Ephesians 6":"Full armor application: Truth (v.14a) — living without deception. Righteousness (v.14b) — knowing your identity in Christ guards the heart from accusation. Gospel readiness (v.15) — staying grounded in the good news. Faith (v.16) — active trust that deflects doubt. Salvation (v.17a) — the settled assurance of being saved guards the mind. Word of God (v.17b) — Scripture as offensive weapon. Prayer (v.18) — the atmosphere of the whole. Discussion: Which piece of armor is most neglected in your daily life?","Philippians 4":"Writing context: Paul writes from prison in Rome, awaiting a verdict that could mean death. The repeated call to rejoice is not denial of hardship but testimony to a joy that hardship cannot destroy. Teaching note: The word 'contentment' (autarkes, v.11) is a Stoic term Paul deliberately reframes — the Stoics found contentment in self-sufficiency; Paul finds it in Christ-sufficiency. Discussion: What is the difference between 'having enough' contentment and 'Christ-is-enough' contentment?","Hebrews 11":"Pedagogical structure: The author presents faith not as an abstract quality but through concrete examples. Each hero is introduced with 'by faith' — showing that faith is always expressed through action. Note: The list does not only include the morally pure (Rahab, Samson, Jacob). Discussion: What does the inclusion of flawed characters in the faith hall of fame tell us about how God works? Application: What action would faith lead you to take that you are currently holding back?","James 1":"Author and audience: James writes to Jewish Christians scattered by persecution — people familiar with trials. His tone is direct, practical, intensely applied. Key structural feature: verses 2-4 establish the framework (trials → endurance → maturity) that the entire letter unpacks. Application: James doesn't explain why trials happen — he explains what they produce. What has a previous trial produced in you that you can recognize as spiritual growth?","Revelation 1":"Genre and context: Revelation is apocalyptic literature — a type of writing common in Jewish and early Christian contexts when communities were under pressure, using symbolic imagery to communicate hope and call to faithfulness. The vision of Christ in chapter 1 establishes the authority and character of the One who sends the seven letters. Teaching point: Before reading any of Revelation's visions of difficulty and judgment, we encounter the glorified, victorious Christ. He is the frame through which all else is interpreted."}},o=[];export{t as C,o as P,e as Q};
